Mobile IPv6 roaming example
============================

A Mobile IPv6 (RFC 3775) scenario with THREE access networks, in which a
single mobile node (MN) performs two successive handovers:

    home network (AP_Home, behind the home agent)
        -> foreign network 1 (AP_1, behind router R_1)
        -> foreign network 2 (AP_2, behind router R_2_acc)

As the MN roams it forms a new care-of address (CoA) in each foreign network
via stateless address autoconfiguration and re-registers it with its home
agent. A correspondent node (CN) pings the MN's stable home address (HoA)
throughout the run; the traffic follows the MN across both handovers, with
only a brief interruption each time the MN moves and re-establishes
connectivity (home-agent registration plus return routability / route
optimization with the CN).

Topology:

    CN --- switch --- backbone --- Home_Agent --- AP_Home   (home network)
                          |
                          +------- R_1 ---------- AP_1       (foreign net 1)
                          |
                          +------- R_2_acc ------ AP_2       (foreign net 2)

The home agent and the access routers are interconnected through a backbone
router; the correspondent node hangs off an Ethernet switch. Addresses and
routes are assigned by the (modern) Ipv6NetworkConfigurator, configured with
assignAddressesToHosts = false so that hosts -- in particular the mobile node
-- autoconfigure their home and care-of addresses.

Run:

    inet -u Cmdenv -c Roaming

or open omnetpp.ini in the IDE / Qtenv and run the "Roaming" configuration.

This example notably exercises route optimization across more than one
handover, which the single-handover examples do not.
